I'm submitting an opinion piece arguing that most companies are responding =
to the pandemic-prompted shift to remote work by trying to exert more digit=
al control over workers. This is going to hurt them for both technical and =
behavioral reasons. Moreover, there is huge opportunity in creating specifi=
c types of technical support for newly autonomous employees.

What's counterintuitive about this is that the technical support needed is =
in empowering employees even further, and specifically in empowering them t=
o communicate between each other over behavioral metrics - not up or down t=
he management hierarchy.

Managers need to know this because we're in a very narrow window of unprece=
dented technology adoption, and first movers will see significant advantage=
 long-term -  especially as we come out of COVID-19 disruption.

This work builds on my last two books - Reputation Economics (McMillan) and=
 Hacking Work (Penguin) - as well as my consulting work to Fortune-400 exec=
utives from BP to Ford to Merck. Additionally, I co-founded IndigoMetrics, =
a company focused in statistically modeling employee behavior engagement an=
d alignment, and have been working in this space for the last four years.

I've already written the entire article and can send it to you for review f=
or exclusive publication at your convenience.

Many thanks,
